        h3 Grade Evaluation Scores for labs, exercises, assignments, and exams will be posted on Canvas as they are graded.
        h4 Labs - 10%
        ul.none
            li There are 10 total labs in this course, i.e. one to be completed each lecture week.
            li Some parts of the lab will be group work while others will be individual work. You can submit one copy for any portion of the lab that is group work.
            li Labs are graded on a 10-point scale and primarily based on participation and effort, rather than correctness.
            li You are required to bring a laptop to the lab.
            li These labs are supposed to enhance the lectures using hands-on learning.
            li Labs are designed to be finished in 70-90 minutes and graded during lab time by your lab instructor.
            li You can finish up to 3 points of the lab at home and bring it with you to the next week's lab for a grade. You must show your update from the previous lab within the first 15 minutes of the current lab to redeem points on the prior lab, otherwise the work is not accepted.
            li If you have a problem with a lab grade, you must contact your lab instructor through EMAIL within ONE WEEK of receiving your grade. After one week, you will not be able to dispute your grade.

        h4   Recitation Exercises - 20%
        ul.none
            li The recitations consist of 4 designs, 8 peer-to-peer design critiques, and 10 quizzes.
            li Attendance is required for recitations, and YOU WILL RECEIVE A ZERO for the attendance and quiz portion of ANY UNEXCUSED MISSED RECITATION!!!
            li You MUST attend the recitation in which you are registered, unless receiving permission from the professor PRIOR to missing the recitation!!!
            li The recitations are used to check and supplement student understanding, and the grades will be based on designs (40%), quizzes (40%), and critiques (20%).


        h4   Assignments - 30%
        ul.none
            li There are 6 total assignments to be completed over the course of this class.
            li DO NOT expect answers to emails about assignments after 5pm on the day it is due!!!
            li All assignments include writing a computer program, which MUST compile and execute on ENGR. There will be written explanations of the solution to turn in (as a pdf) with each implementation.
            li Programming assignments that do not compile will receive a grade of zero.
            li Assignments are to be turned in before Midnight (<strong>by 11:59pm) on Sunday night, otherwise the assignment is late.
            li Programs are evaluated on how well they solve the assigned problem (adherence to program specification), proper formatting/use of comments, and creativity:)
            li Only one late assignment, up to 5 days late, is accepted without any penalty. All other late assignments will not be graded. You turn in your assignment to TEACH, just as you would normally.
            li You will turn in your assignments through hand-in on the <a style="color:#0000FF" href="https://secure.engr.oregonstate.edu:8000/teach.php?type=want_auth"> TEACH website</a>. All assignments are turned into TEACH, and designs are turned into CANVAS!!!
            li EVERY assignment in this course is graded by demoing your work for 10 minutes with a TA. You are required to meet with a TA within two weeks from the due date to demo. You are penalized for failure to demo within two weeks or missing a scheduled appointment.
            ol.space
                li Failure to demo within two weeks receives an automatic 50 point deduction.
                li If you miss a scheduled appointment without informing the TA PRIOR to the appointment, then you lose 10 points for rescheduling within 24 hours, 25 points within a week, and anything rescheduled outside of a week is an automatic 50 point deduction.
            li If you have a problem with an assignment grade, you must contact your TAs through EMAIL within ONE WEEK of receiving your grade. After one week, you will not be able to dispute your grade.
            li Remember to use your TAs because they are the ones who execute, read, and grade the assignments.


